        <fr:anchor>25099</fr:anchor>
        <fr:title text="Related">Related</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>25096</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-016X</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-016X.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Derivations">Derivations</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>In the presence of a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">syntactic rules</fr:link> describing a subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, a <fr:em><fr:strong>derivation</fr:strong></fr:em> that a particular element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> lies in that subset is given by a finite tree with vertices labelled by elements of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> such that:</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li>the root of the tree is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>;</fr:li>
 <fr:li>each vertex of the tree is the <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">conclusion</fr:link> of a rule whose <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">premises</fr:link> are the children of the node</fr:li>
 <fr:li>each leaf of the tree is an <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">axiom</fr:link>.</fr:li></fr:ol>
            <fr:p>Viewing a tree as growing upwards from the root, we have the following derivation for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[3\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> in when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex> is the two rules from <fr:link href="jms-016T.xml" title="Syntactic rules for forming natural numbers" addr="jms-016T" type="local">Example <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-016T" /></fr:link>:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle 
  
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle 
   
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle 
    
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle }{\displaystyle \quad 0\quad }


   }{\displaystyle \quad 1\quad }


  }{\displaystyle \quad 2\quad }


 }{\displaystyle \quad 3\quad }


]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>25097</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-016U</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-016U.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="The closure condition denoted by a syntactic rule">The closure condition denoted by a <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">syntactic rule</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">syntactic rule</fr:link> like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[
 \scriptstyle \frac {\scriptstyle u_1\quad \ldots \quad  u_n}{\scriptstyle v}
]]></fr:tex> on a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> denotes a <fr:em>closure condition</fr:em> on subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, i.e. a subset of the powerset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {P}{\mathopen {}\left (X\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. In particular, the meaning of this rule is the following subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {P}{\mathopen {}\left (X\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 {\mathopen {}\left \{S\subseteq  X\,\middle \vert \,
  u_1,\ldots ,u_n\in  S\implies 
  v\in  S
 \right \}\mathclose {}}
]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex> is a set of <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">rules</fr:link> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, we will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}\subseteq  \mathcal {P}{\mathopen {}\left (X\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for the intersection of the closure conditions denoted by each rule in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex>. This is, in other words, the set of subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> that lie in the <fr:link href="jms-016U.xml" title="The closure condition denoted by a syntactic rule" addr="jms-016U" type="local">closure condition</fr:link> for each <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">rule</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in  \mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>25098</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-016S</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-016S.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Syntactic rule">Syntactic rule</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The basic form of a rule that describes a subset of a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is as follows:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \frac {
  u_1 \quad  \ldots  \quad  u_n
 }{
  v
 }
]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>The plain English meaning of the rule is: <fr:em>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_1]]></fr:tex> through <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_n]]></fr:tex> are elements of the subset that I am defining, then so is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>.</fr:em> In such a rule, the items on top of the horizontal line are called <fr:em><fr:strong>premises</fr:strong></fr:em> or <fr:em><fr:strong>antecedents</fr:strong></fr:em> or <fr:em><fr:strong>hypotheses</fr:strong></fr:em>, and the item on the bottom of the horizontal line is called the <fr:em><fr:strong>conclusion</fr:strong></fr:em>. When a rule has no premises, it is called an <fr:em><fr:strong>axiom</fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
